A. Returns¶

From the summary depicted below it is visible that mean is positive while median is zero for returns. This indicates that should there be skewness, it is positive. The histogram below shows roughly symmetric distribution so just by visual inspection, skewness is very marginal. Altogether the returns are centered around zero, which is in line with expecations. Otherwise, it would be easy to gain/lose on this stock. The plot of the returns over our sample period suggests a stationary process as mean and variance look relatively stable. Correlograms below display the ACF (autocorrelation function) and PACF (partial autocorrelation function). From the correlograms it can be observed that there is minimal autocorrelation in the returns - only 14, 15, 18 and 27th lags are significant, otherwise there is no significance. Overall, there does not seem to be much dependence that could be captured by models. To test stationarity (not just visually), ADF (Augmented Dickey Fuller test) is used. The test confirms our prediction on stationarity and the null hypothesis of non-stationary data is rejected with p-value smaller than 0.01. In addition to stationarity, we check normality of the returns. Histogram below suggest that returns are leptocurtic and have heavy tails in comparison to the normal distribution, as most of the asset returns. This means that extremely large returns (positive or negative) are more likely to occur than in the standard normal distribution.

C. Realized skewness and realized kurtosis¶

A mean value of kurtosis 6.037 suggests that the distribution of RV has a relatively high peak and heavy tails compared to a normal distribution. It indicates that the data has a greater concentration of values around the mean and more extreme values in the tails compared to a normal distribution, as it was already suggested in the histogram of returns. Thus, there is a higher probability of extreme events or outliers occurring. When we look at kurtosis through a different optic - as volatility of volatility - we see that RV fluctuates over time, which is also visible from initial graph. A mean skewness value of 0.02307 suggests that the distribution is approximately symmetric. A skewness value of zero would indicate perfect symmetry, but in our case a small positive skewness suggests a slight imbalance in the distribution, namely right-skewed distribution with the long tail on its right side. In the context of asset returns, a right-skewed distribution suggests that there is a higher probability of observing positive or higher returns compared to negative or lower returns. Overall, realised skewness is in line with expectations as it is centered around zero and resembles white noise, i.e. there is no free lunch.

2. In-sample fit¶

In this section, parameters of the following volatility models of the full sample size will be estimated: AR(1)-RV, HAR, HAR-RS, HAR-Rskew-RKurt, Realized GARCH, ARMA-GARCH. We start with creating lag of all the variables.

In [16]:
adm$RV_lag <- shift(adm$RV)
adm$RV5_lag <- frollmean(adm$RV_lag, 5)
adm$RV22_lag <- frollmean(adm$RV_lag, 22)
adm$RV_p_lag <- shift(adm$RV_p)
adm$RV_n_lag <- shift(adm$RV_n)
adm$RS_lag <- shift(adm$RS)
adm$RK_lag <- shift(adm$RK)

A. AR(1)-RV¶

We start with estimation of the first-order autoregressive model, that has the following form:

$$RV_t = \alpha + \beta * RV_{t-1} + \epsilon_t$$

Thre intuition behind this model is that the realized volatility (RV) in time t depends linearly on its own previous value in time t-1. From the below estimated output is it visible that this holds as the estimated coefficient on RV_lag is significantly positive. However, it might be beneficial to extend the model for other lags, or used another model. This is suggested also by ACF and PACF of residuals which show some significant lags meaning we are still dealing with the dependence. However, since ACF of RV shows slow decay, RV might follow more complicated process and so AR(1) cannot be a good fit.

2. HAR¶

Since AR(1)-RV has been proven as not very good fit for the data and the long memory is suspected, heterogeneous autoregressive model (HAR) is employed. Its form is depicted as:

$$RV_t = \alpha + \beta_1 * RV_{t-1} + \beta_2 * RV_{t-1}^{(5)} + \beta_3 * RV_{t-1}^{(22)} + \epsilon_t$$

where $RV_{t-1}^{(h)}$ is h-period realized volatility. The main idea behind the HAR model is based on different behavior of investors, hence term "heterogeneous". The behavior is captured by different investment horizons of traders, 1-day, 5-days (week) and 22-days (month).

From the model depicted below we can see that the estimated coefficients on 1-day, 5-days and 22-days realized volatilities are all significant and positive. This suggests that AR(1) process from previous part is not a good fit since more distant lags are significant as well. Improvement in comparison to the simple AR(1) model is suggested also by a bit higher R-squared and less significant lags in ACF and PACF correlograms. However, significant lags are still present (albeit marginally) and R-squared has not improved by much, thus extensions of HAR or other models might be handy.

3. HAR-RS¶

Since $RV_t=RV^+_{t}+RV^-_{t}$, including $RV^+_{t-1}+RV^-_{t-1}$ instead of $RV_{t-1}$ can depict the effect of "bad" and "good" volatility separately. Thus, this variation of heterogeneous autoregressive model will take following form:

$$RV_t = \alpha + \beta_0 * RV^+_{t-1} + \beta_1 * RV^-_{t-1} + \beta_2 * RV_{t-1}^{(5)} + \beta_3 * RV_{t-1}^{(22)} + \epsilon_t$$

From the output below it is clear that past "bad" volatility increases volatility more than past "good" volatility, which is in line with empirical findings. Correlograms of ACF and PACF look very similar to the previous ones.

4. HAR-RSkew-RKurt¶

Another possibility is to extend the standard HAR for realized skewness and realized kurtosis. Such a model will be estimated as:

$$RV_t = \alpha + \beta_1 * RV_{t-1} + \beta_2 * RV_{t-1}^{(5)} + \beta_3 * RV_{t-1}^{(22)} + \beta_4 * RSkew_{t-1} + \beta_5 * RKurt_{t-1} + \epsilon_t$$

From the output depicted below we can see that the estimated coefficients on 1-day and 5-days realized volatilities still remain significant at 1% significance level as in standard HAR model. However, the significance of 22-days realized volatility decreased. Moreoever, the effect of these variables decreased as well after including additional variables, even though the direction remains the same. The estimates on realized skewness and realized kurtosis are both negative and significant, however, the effect of realized skewness is significant only at 10% significance level. The adjusted $R^2$ is the highest among HAR models. All in all, including additional variables definitely improves the fit.

5. ARMA-GARCH¶

In order to estimate GARCH model, mean equation needs to be specified. Using selection procedure based on Akaike information criterion (AIC) and Bayesian Information Criteria (BIC), ARMA(0,0) is reported to be the best fit indicating that there is no autoregressive, differencing, or moving average component included in the mean equation. Thus, this mean equation has the following form:

$$r_{t}=c+\epsilon_{t}$$

where c is some constant.

Homoscedasticity of the residuals at the lowest lags is rejected by employing ARCH-LM test. Jarque-Bera test is applied to test normality of models residuals. The test rejects the null hypothesis of normality at any commonly used level of significance, signalling conditional heteroskedasticity being present in the data. Thus, we model ARMA-GARCH to account for it. Standard GARCH is used given by:

$$\sigma^2_{t}=\omega+\sum_{i=1}^{p}\alpha_{i}u^2_{t-i}+\sum_{j=1}^{q} \beta_{j}\sigma^2_{t-j}$$

ARMA(0,0)-GARCH(1,1) is shown to be the best fit for the data, minimizing the BIC (various models up to GARCH(5,5) has been tested). As per results of the model estimation, $\omega$ is the constant term in the conditional variance equation and represents the long-run average variance. Positive value of $\alpha$ indicates that past squared errors have a positive effect on the current variance. $\beta$ parameter measures the persistence of the conditional variance. It is close to 1 which means that shocks to the variance are long-lasting and take a long time to dissipate. There are no signs of bias which suggests that there should not be leverage effect present. We moreover tested null hypothesis of Weighted ARCH LM Test which suggests that the ARCH process is adequately fitted. The results indicate that the null hypothesis cannot be rejected at all commonly used levels of significance.

# find the best GARCH model based on the BIC
p_max <- 5
q_max <- 5
aic_min <- Inf
best_p <- 0
best_q <- 0

for (i1 in 1:p_max) {
    for (i2 in 1:q_max) {
        garchspec <- ugarchspec(mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0, 0), include.mean = TRUE), 
                     variance.model = list(model = 'sGARCH', garchOrder = c(i1, i2)))
        garch_fit <- ugarchfit(spec = garchspec, data = adm$ret)
        inf_crit <- infocriteria(garch_fit)[2] #1 aic, 2 bic
        aic_min <- ifelse(inf_crit < aic_min, inf_crit, aic_min)
        
        best_p <- ifelse(inf_crit == aic_min, i1, best_p)
        best_q <- ifelse(inf_crit == aic_min, i2, best_q)
    }
}

c(best_p, best_q)

# specify the model that we want to estimate
garchspec <- ugarchspec(mean.model = list(armaOrder = c(0, 0), include.mean = TRUE), 
                     variance.model = list(garchOrder = c(best_p, best_q)))
# estimate the model
garch_fit <- ugarchfit(spec = garchspec, data = adm$ret)

6. Realized GARCH¶

Since GARCH takes information from returns to adjust value of conditional variance but is updating slowly, using realized GARCH that includes realized volatility in the volatility equation can come in handy. Using realized GARCH may hugely improve the fit. Thus, complete realized GARCH takes form:

\begin{align} r_t= & \sqrt{h_t}z_t \\ ln(h_t)= & \omega + \beta ln(h_{t-1})+\alpha ln(RV_{t-1})\\ ln(RV_t)= & \xi+ \varphi ln(h_t) + u_t \end{align}

ARMA(0,0)-realGARCH(1,1) is estimated with BIC lower than in the standard GARCH.

In [30]:

    mean.model = list(armaOrder=c(0, 0), include.mean=FALSE))
real_garch_fit<- ugarchfit(real_garchspec, adm$ret, solver = 'gosolnp', realizedVol = sqrt(adm$RV))

Comparison of the models¶

Finally, we compare invidiual models visually.

We start with AR(1) and HAR models. From the figures below, we see that AR(1) model is more noisy than HAR models and that it inflates true volatility proxied by RV. This is applicable to some periods. Neverthless, superiority of the models is attributed to HAR family. The fits are generally very similar to each other. We expect this since the models yield similar estimates and showed similar characteristics.

Let's try to plot RV with GARCH and Realized GARCH in one figure. We see that classical GARCH overestimates RV more than Realized GARCH. Nevertheless, neither of the models seem to capture RV sufficiently. This is by the construction as GARCH models volatility as a latent process and behaves like a filter. Overall, HAR models outperform GARCH models as well.

3. Forecasts¶

In this section, we proceed with forecasts of volatility based on the models specificed above. As suggested, initial window length is set to 750 observations. Total number of observations is 1500, so the second 750 observations is the testing set. For AR(1) and HAR models we do not follow seminar 11 but rather use simple predict() function. This is driven by the fact that we work with more complex HAR models. Plots of individual forecasts are visualized after all models are taken care of.

AR(1) and HAR models - rolling & expanding¶

In the beginning, we specify the window length and number of forecast outputs. Then we set aside true RV so we can compare our forecasts to it. Finally, we prepare an object of logical values which we will replace by the forecast. We have tried to create a list object for each item as well but that turned out to be rather clumsy.

In [35]:
w_l <- 750
n_for <- 750
RV_true <- adm$RV[751:1500]

HAR_RS_roll <- rep(NA, 750)
HAR_RS_RK_exp <- rep(NA, 750)
HAR_RS_RK_roll <- rep(NA, 750)

We start with rolling window. Simply for each model specification, we shift the window and save a newly forecast value. We proceed analogically with expanding window below. This time, however, training set is altered so it really is expanding.

In [36]:
# rolling
for (i in 0:(750-1)) {
    training <- adm[(start + i):(end + i), ]                 
    testing <- adm[end + i + 1,]
    
    AR1_RV <- lm(RV ~ RV_lag, data=training)
    AR1_roll[i + 1] <- predict(AR1_RV, newdata=testing)
    
    HAR <- lm(RV ~ RV_lag + RV5_lag + RV22_lag, data=training)
    HAR_roll[i + 1] <- predict(HAR, newdata=testing)
    
    HAR_RS <- lm(RV ~ RV_p_lag + RV_n_lag + RV5_lag + RV22_lag, data=training)
    HAR_RS_roll[i + 1] <- predict(HAR_RS, newdata=testing)
    
    HAR_RS_RK <- lm(RV ~ RV_lag + RV5_lag + RV22_lag + RS_lag + RK_lag, data=training)
    HAR_RS_RK_roll[i + 1] <- predict(HAR_RS_RK, newdata=testing)
}

Realized GARCH - rolling and expanding¶

We faced obstacles when forecasting based on Realized GARCH. Therefore, to avoid convergence failures, we used different solver than before. Note that "hybrid" solver first uses "solnp" and then proceeds with other solvers should there be a problem. Strangely enough, we still faced convergence failures. Therefore, we resumed the procedure as was suggested. At first we tried "solnp" solver but without any result. On a second try, "gosolnp" solver worked.

Plots¶

Finally, we plot all forecasts. We can quickly observe that forecasts based on HAR models are quite similar within and between each other. AR(1) forecasts stand out a bit as they tends to inflate volatility. Regarding, AR(1) forecasts, approach utilizing rolling window seems to be a better fit because it inflates volatility to lower extent. This is in line with our intuition. However, HAR models seem to be more appropriate compared to AR(1). But when inspected visually, we cannot distinguish which HAR model is better and which forecast scheme is better as they are all quite similar. Therefore, further comparisons regarding forecast errors are necessary.

Regarding ARMA-GARCH forecasts, they are inappropriate because they overestimate volatility a lot. We also see that the forecasts are lagged which is visible over the whole horizon. This stems from the fact that GARCH is updating rather slowly. When we compare the two schemes (rolling vs expanding), rolling window naturally provides less lagged forecasts as old observations are discarded from memory.

Forecast Errors¶

In this subsection, we plot forecast errors and conduct analysis on the performance of individual models. The goal is to select the best one.

We begin by computing loss functions and then run Diebold-Mariano tests utilizing the MSE loss function. Finally, we challange each model forecast with Mincer-Zarnowitz regression.

Forecast error is essentially the difference between the true value and the forecast. Naturally, we expect and would like to achieve the error to be zero. Therefore, we expect the plotted errors to oscillate around zero.

When we look at the figures above, we indeed confirm our intuition about error means. We can also observe some common factors. For instance, there are regular occurrences of error spikes in all predictions. The errors overall look similar. ARMA-GARCH seems to perform worse due to higher volatility of errors. Realized GARCH performs better compared to ARMA-GARCH which is not surprising. However, just visual inspection is not enough. Therefore, we proceed with computation of loss functions.

Firstly, let's define MAE and MSE as:

$$MAE: \mathscr{L}(RV_{t+1},\hat{RV_{t+1|t})}=|RV_{t+h}-\hat{RV_{t+h|t}}|$$$$MSE: \mathscr{L}(RV_{t+1},\hat{RV_{t+1|t})}=(RV_{t+h}-\hat{RV_{t+h|t}})^2$$

Naturally, we would like to minizime these functions, which would imply higher accuracy of the predictions. Key difference between the two measures is the fact that MSE penalizes large forecast errors more compared to MAE. This is due to the power in the exponent. Let's compute them now.

Firstly, let's mention that it might not make sense to compare MAE with MSE since they both have different construction. Therefore, we focus only on differences within each score. When looking at MAE, errors are minimized for HAR models - especially HAR_RS_RK performs the best. This conclusion holds for both prediction schemes. Should we choose between rolling and expanding window, HAR_RS_RK utilizing rolling window is our candidate. The worst performance is noted by ARMA-GARCH. Regarding MSE, the same conclusion can be reached. The only distinction is that error for HAR_RS_RK is lower under expanding scheme compared to rolling window.

Now, let's turn our focus to Diebold-Mariano test that check for differences in accuracy of forecasts. In the following section, we work with MSE loss. The logic is such that under the null hypothesis, the losses are the same and hence the models have statistically identical accuracy.

The tests centres around loss differential: $d_t=\mathscr{L_{1,t}}-\mathscr{L_{2,t}}$.

We assume that $d_t$ is stationary. The null of the DM test is $H^0: E[d_t]=0$

$DM - T = \frac{\sqrt{T}\bar{d}}{\sqrt{T}} \overset{a}{\sim} N(0,1)$,

where $\bar{d}=T^{-1}\Sigma_{t} d_t,\omega$ is its asymptotic variance. The $\omega$ is estimated as sample variance of $d_t$.

The null hypothesis is that the two methods have the same forecast accuracy. For alternative="less", the alternative hypothesis is that method 2 is less accurate than method 1. For alternative="greater", the alternative hypothesis is that method 2 is more accurate than method 1. For alternative="two.sided", the alternative hypothesis is that method 1 and method 2 have different levels of accuracy.

We begin testing each model and difference between the schemes.

In [104]:

Before we reach final conclusion, let's conduct Mincer-Zarnowitz regressions. In this regression, we regress true values on forecasts, i.e.:

$$RV_{t+h}=\alpha+\beta\hat{RV_{t+h|t}}+\epsilon_t$$

for $h=1,2,...$

The null hypothesis: $H^0: \alpha = 0 \cup \beta=1$, which means that forecast matches true values. We conduct this regression for all models and all schemes. We comment on the results afterwards.

After running many regressions, we could quickly see that GARCH models do not perform Mincer-Zarnowitz regression very well. Intecept is statistically indifferent from zero and the estimated coefficient is far from 1. Furthermore, $R^2$ is low (especially for ARMA-GARCH). Other models perform better. We could conclude that all models, except for GARCH models, do not reject the null hypothesis of intercept being equal to 0 or the estimated coefficient being equal to 1. We can also observe that $R^2$ increases as we move from simpler models to more complex ones. $R^2$ is then highest for HAR_RS_RK expanding window approach, which indicates highest accuracy among all considered specifications.

4. Summary¶

In this empirical project we try to model realized volatility of Archer-Daniels-Midland Co. (ADM) stock and evaluate predictive ability of the models, six in total - AR(1), HAR, HAR_RS, HAR_RS_RK, ARMA-GARCH and Realized GARCH - to provide future estimates of volatility.

We compare in-sample fits corresponding to each model and elaborate by visual inspection. The best in-sample estimation performance is reached by the HAR family models - their fiited values mimic the actual realized volatility more accurately than AR(1) or GARCH models. Therefore, due to statistical significance of estimated coefficients and higherst $R^2$, HAR_RS_RK is potential candidate for forecasting.

To predict volatility, we divide the sample into two parts - training and testing sets of equal length - and provide forecasts utilizing all six models from the prior section of this project. Additionally, for each predition we use two different approaches - rolling window and expanding window. The out-of-sample forecasting performance of the models is tested by comparison of mean square errors (MSE) and mean absolute errors (MAE). We proceed to distinguish between two model forecasts using Diebold-Mariano test and then test individual forecasts using Mincer-Zarnowitz regression. HAR models are shown to outperform AR(1) and GARCH models also in out-of-sample forecasts no matter the scheme (rolling vs expanding). The MAE and MSE are both minimized for HAR_RS_RK in particular for both expanding and rolling windows, suggesting that HAR_RS_RK estimates the volatility most precisely among all six models. This is then confirmed by Diebold-Mariano tests as well, that compare the models pairwise, HAR_RS_RK turned out to be the best performer. Finally, we employed the Mincer-Zarnowitz regression to examine forecast accuracy of all single model forecasts. Results of the Mincer-Zarnowitz regressions suggest that $R^2$ is the highest for HAR_RS_RK expanding window approach, which indicates highest accuracy among all considered specifications. All in all, after taking into account outcomes of various methods used for assessing the forecasting accuracy, results lead us to conclusion that the HAR_RS_RK is the best choice to model and predict volatility of ADM stock.
